{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{Use British English|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox Artwork | image_file=John Constable 027.jpg | title=Weymouth Bay | artist=[[John Constable]] | year=1816–17 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=53 | width_metric=75 | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[London]] | museum=[[National Gallery, London|National Gallery]] }}
'''''Weymouth Bay: Bowleaze Cove and Jordon Hill''''' was painted by the leading [[England|English]] landscape artist [[John Constable]] in 1816–17. The painting now hangs in the [[National Gallery, London]].<ref>[http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/paintings/john-constable-weymouth-bay-bowleaze-cove-and-jordon-hill Weymouth Bay: Bowleaze Cove and Jordon Hill], [[The National Gallery]], London, UK.</ref>
In October 1816, Constable spent his honeymoon at the village of [[Osmington]] near the seaside town of [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]] in [[Dorset]]. The idea for this painting dates from this period. The painting shows a view of [[Weymouth Bay]] on the south coast of [[England]], looking west. The painting includes [[Bowleaze Cove]], [[Jordan Hill, Dorset|Jordan Hill]]. and the small Jordan River flowing over the beach, with [[Furzy Cliff]] behind. Beyond that in the far distance is the beach at [[Greenhill, Dorset|Greenhill]].
A larger version of the painting called ''Osmington Shore'' was exhibited by Constable at the [[British Institution]] in 1819.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}}
