{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=The ashes of phocion collected by his widow 1648.jpg | image_size=350px | title=Landscape with the Ashes of Phocion | artist=[[Nicolas Poussin]] | year=1648 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=116.5 | width_metric=178.5 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Liverpool]] | museum=[[Walker Art Gallery]] }} '''''Landscape with the Ashes of Phocion''''' is a 1648 painting, also known as '''''Landscape with the Ashes of Phocion (Collected by His Widow)''''' and '''''The Ashes of Phocion Collected by his Widow''''', by French artist [[Nicolas Poussin]]. [[Phocion]] was an [[Athens|Athenian]] statesman from the 4th century BC.
"It is a picture about exile. Phocion, an Athenian general, was falsely condemned and executed, and his unburied corpse banished, and taken to the outskirts of [[Megara]] where it was burnt. At the very front his faithful widow gathers up his ashes. Her servant keeps look out. And the outcasts are placed directly below the mighty nucleus of temple-rock-cloud. But nothing in the scene indicates that the civilisation from which they're excluded is itself evil, corrupt or doomed, that they're well out of it. No, their exile from the good life is sheer tragedy. The majestic symphony of the city continues undiminished."<ref> Tom Lubbock, ''The Independent ''Britains Art Treasures, no.11 </ref> The painting is housed at the [[Walker Art Gallery]], part of the [[National Museums Liverpool]], [[England]].<ref name=WAG>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/collections/17c/poussin.aspx|title='Landscape with the ashes of Phocion', Nicolas Poussin, 1648|publisher=National Museums Liverpool|accessdate=2008-09-15|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914032320/http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/collections/17c/poussin.aspx|archivedate=2008-09-14|df=}}</ref>
The same year Poussin painted a companion piece to ''Landscape with the Ashes of Phocion'', ''[[The Funeral of Phocion]]'', in three versions. Another version of this painting is in the [[Holburne Museum]].<ref>[https://artuk.org/discover/artworks/the-ashes-of-phocion-collected-by-his-widow-39423 The Ashes of Phocion Collected by His Widow] in the Holburne Museum on [[Art UK]]</ref>
