[[Image:View of Geelong 1856 painting.jpg|right|thumb|300px|View of Geelong, painted by [[Johann Joseph Eugen von Guerard]] in [[1856 in art|1856]].]]
:''Throughout this article, the $ symbol refers to the [[Australian dollar]].''<!-- Disclaimer is as per Wikipedia:Manual of Style (dates and numbers) #Currency -->
'''''View of Geelong''''' is an 1856 [[oil painting]] on canvas by [[Eugene von Guerard]]. The painting measures 154.5x89cm and is owned by the [[Geelong Art Gallery]] in Victoria, Australia.<ref>[http://collections.geelonggallery.org.au/emuwebgag/pages/gag/Display.php?irn=4937 View of Geelong]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} at the Geelong Gallery</ref>
It was purchased from English composer [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] for $3.8M. The purchase is the second highest ever for an Australian work of art, with the top being $5.3M paid by the [[National Gallery of Australia]] for a portrait of [[Captain James Cook]] by [[John Webber]]. [http://www.heraldsun.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5478,19709055%255E2902,00.html]{{dead link|date=June 2014}}
Lloyd Webber had bought the painting in 1996 for A$1.98 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/arts/lloyd-webber-sells-geelong-masterpiece/2006/05/12/1146940719620.html&cid=0&ei=nBhwRIz2C4W6pwK9qZWOCw|title=Lloyd Webber sells Geelong masterpiece|date=12 May 2006|journal=The Age}}</ref>
In 1996, the painting was loaned to the Geelong Art Gallery, where it proved popular.<ref name="sixslayings">[http://www.geelonggallery.org.au/events/view_of_geelong.htm The future of a Geelong icon needs your support], Geelong Art Gallery {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928103221/http://www.geelonggallery.org.au/events/view_of_geelong.htm |date=September 28, 2007 }}</ref>
In 2005, Lloyd Webber offered the painting for sale via auction house [[Christie's]] of [[London]], giving the Geelong Gallery first right of refusal. On July 7, 2006, the Geelong Gallery purchased the painting for permanent display in the Geelong Gallery, after being offered $1.5 million from the Victorian state government and the remainder being sought via a community fundraising appeal.
