'''''An East View of the Great Cataract of Niagara''''' is a historic [[watercolour painting|watercolour]] of [[Niagara Falls]] painted on site by [[Thomas Davies (British Army officer)|Thomas Davies]] ({{circa|1737}}–1812) in 1762. It was the first eyewitness painting and the first accurate view of the falls.<ref name=christie1>{{cite web|title=Captain Thomas Davies (1737–1812): An East View of the Great Cataract of Niagara|url=http://www.christies.com/lotfinder/drawings-watercolors/captain-thomas-davies-an-east-view-5873997-details.aspx|publisher=[[Christie's]]|date=1 April 2015}}</ref>{{sfnp|Dickenson|1998|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=MHET0UM9Q40C&pg=PA195 p. 195]}}

==History==
[[Thomas Davies (British Army officer)|Thomas Davies]] was a British Army officer in the [[Royal Artillery]] and received training in topographic drawing at the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]]. During the [[French and Indian War]], he served under General [[Jeffery Amherst, 1st Baron Amherst|Jeffery Amherst]].<ref name=dcb>{{cite book|last=Hubbard|first=R. H.|chapter=Davies, Thomas|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/davies_thomas_5E.html|title=Dictionary of Canadian Biography|volume=5|publisher=University of Toronto|year=1983}}</ref> After the [[Battle of the Thousand Islands|attack against Montreal]], he surveyed the surrounding region from 1760 to 1766 and painted six waterfalls, including this one of [[Niagara Falls]].{{sfnp|Dickenson|1998|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=MHET0UM9Q40C&pg=PA195 p. 195]}}

Niagara Falls was first described in the journals of [[Samuel de Champlain]] in 1604.{{sfnp|Dow|1921|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ACYVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA17 pp. 17–19]}} The first published eyewitness description was by [[Louis Hennepin]] in ''Description of Louisiana'' (1683). His later work, ''A New Discovery of a Vast Country'' (1697), included the first image of the falls based on his description and not done on site.{{sfnp|Dow|1921|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ACYVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA23 pp. 23–29]}}<ref name=wink>{{cite web|title=The Winkworth Collection: A Treasure House of Canadiana in London|url=http://www.christies.com/features/Winkworth-5675-1.aspx|publisher=[[Christie's]]|date=23 February 2015}}</ref>

Davies later painted two additional views of the falls {{circa|1766}}. His work was not well known until after a 1953 auction from the [[Earl of Derby]]'s library.<ref name=christie1/>{{sfnp|Hubbard|1972|pp=20–21}} These paintings were then shown as part of a major exhibition devoted to Davies, 2 July – 4 September 1972, at the [[National Gallery of Canada]].{{sfnp|Hubbard|1972|p=4}}

On 1 April 2015, it was sold for £146,500 ($217,260) at [[Christie's]] in [[London]] from the Winkworth Collection.<ref name=christie1/><ref name=wink/> A print of the engraving of this painting by Fougeron was sold for £3,750 ($5,561).<ref name=christie2/> On 19 August 2015, a temporary export bar was placed on the painting in an effort to keep it in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|title=First watercolour of Niagara Falls under threat of leaving UK|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/first-watercolour-of-niagara-falls-under-threat-of-leaving-uk|agency=[[Department for Culture, Media & Sport]]|date=19 August 2015}}</ref>

==Description==
The view is of [[Horseshoe Falls]] from the Canadian bank.<ref name=christie1/> The painting shows a rainbow emerging from the mist, while two [[Iroquois]] watch on the right. The landscape has red and orange colours as the forest leaves change from green in the fall.<ref name=lambourn>{{cite web|last1=Lambourn|first1=Nicholas|title=Niagara Falls – the first view|url=http://www.christies.com/features/Niagara-Falls-5820-1.aspx|publisher=[[Christie's]]|date=25 March 2015}}</ref>

==Inscription==
Davies inscribed scientific notes about the falls and the landscape at the bottom of the work:<ref name=christie1/>
{{Poemquote|
Done on the Spot by Thomas Davies Capt Royal Artillery
The Perpendicular height of the Fall 162 feet Breadth about a Mile & Quarter
The Variety of Colours in the Woods shews the true Nature of the Country
}}

==Other versions==
[[Ignace Fougeron|J. Fougeron]]  produced a handcoloured engraving of this work, published in Davies's ''Six Views of North American Waterfalls'' ({{circa|1763}}–68).<ref name=christie2>{{cite web|title=After Captain Thomas Davies (1737–1812): An East View of the Great Cataract of Niagara|url=http://www.christies.com/lotfinder/drawings-watercolors/captain-thomas-davies-an-east-view-5873998-details.aspx|publisher=[[Christie's]]|date=1 April 2015}}</ref> Davies later painted ''Niagara Falls from Above'' ({{circa|1766}}) and ''Niagara Falls from Below'' ({{circa|1766}}) showing the falls from different perspectives.{{sfnp|Dickenson|1998|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=MHET0UM9Q40C&pg=PA195 p. 195]}} These two are now in the collection of the [[New-York Historical Society]].{{sfnp|Hubbard|1972|pp=98–99}}

